         <head rend="center"><title type="main">Song I.<emph rend="super">1</emph><note type="head"
                  place="bottom"><emph rend="super">1</emph> First published in <emph rend="italic"
                     >Poetical Essays</emph> (1788), p. 213.</note></title></head>
         <note rend="center">Tune. <emph rend="italic">Now or never.</emph><emph rend="super"
               >2</emph></note>
         <note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph rend="super">2</emph> Unidentified.</note>
         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">I.</head>
            <lg>
               <l>Why will you thus my passion scorn,</l>
               <l rend="indent">And will you love me never?</l>
               <l>Will you not grant a kind return?</l>
               <l rend="indent">O do, my dear, be clever. </l>
            </lg>
         </div1>
         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">II.</head>
            <lg>
               <l n="5">Let other youths protest and vow,</l>
               <l rend="indent">And be your slaves for ever;</l>
               <l>’Tis what I’ll always scorn to do:</l>
               <l rend="indent">So pray, my dear, be clever.</l>
            </lg>
         </div1>
         <div1 type="stanza">
            <head rend="center">III.</head>
            <lg>
               <l>Those blushing cheeks will soon turn pale,</l>
               <l n="10" rend="indent">Those eyes no shafts deliver,</l>
               <l>Then, Chloe,<emph rend="super">3</emph><note type="gloss" place="bottom"><emph
                        rend="super">3</emph> Character in a Greek pastoral romance, <emph
                        rend="italic">Daphnis and Chloe</emph>, often attributed to Longus; Cf.
                     Alexander Pope, <emph rend="italic">Moral Essays</emph>, ii.157 and Matthew
                     Prior, “Answer. To Chloe Jealous” in <emph rend="italic">Poems on Several
                        Occasions</emph> (1707). </note> ev’ry art will fail,</l>
               <l rend="indent">So pray, my dear, be clever. </l>
            </lg>
         </div1>


